    Kubernetes(K8s)

-> It is an open-source container orchestration platform orignally developed by Google. 
   It automates the deployment, scaling, and managment of containerized application
   across clusters of hosts,

    (why K8s?) 

=> without K8s

-> manual container managment
-> no automatic scaling
-> Complex networking setup
-> manual failover and recovery
-> limited resource optimisation

=> with K8s

-> automated deployment and rollbacks
-> automatic scaling (horizontal and vertical)
-> Self-healing capabilities
-> Service discovery and load balancing
-> Storage Orchestration
-> Secret and configuration management

    K8s features:

i) Networking
    -> Service Discovery
    -> Load Balancing
    -> DNS management

ii) Storage
    -> Storage Classes
    -> Persistent Volumes
    -> Dynamic Provisioning

iii) Orchestration
    -> Pod Scheduling
    -> Resource Allocation
    -> Container Management

iv) Scaling 
    -> Cluster Autoscaling 
    -> Vertical Pod Autoscaling 
    -> Horizontal Pod Autoscaling

v) High Availability
    -> Health checks
    -> Self healing 
    -> Auto scaling

    K8s Ecosystem:

-> kubectl: Command-line tool for interacting with clusters
-> helm: Package manager for k8s
-> Operators: Extend k8s functionality
-> Service Mesh: Istio, Linkerd for advanced networking
-> Monitoring: Prometheus, Grafana for observability

    K8s Architecture:

-> It follows master-slave(control plane-node) architecture.

    Master: 

-> etcd:
    -> Consistent and highly-available key-value store
    -> Stores all cluster data including configuration, state, and metadata
    -> Provides distributed consensus
    -> Can be restored for disaster recovery
    -> Critical for cluster state persistence
-> API server: 
    -> Centeral management entity and primary entry point for all REST commands.
    -> Exposes the K8s HTTP API
    -> Validates and processes API requests
    -> Serves as the frontend for the control panel
    -> All components communicate through API server
-> Scheduler:
    -> Watches for newly created Pods without assignned nodes
    -> Selects optimal nodes for each Pod based on:
        - Resource requiremtns (CPU, memory)
        - Hadware/software constraints
        - Affinity and anti-affinity rules
        - Data locality
        - Workload interference
-> Controller Manager:
    -> Runs controller processes to implement K8s API behaviour
    -> Includes multiple controllers:
        - Node Controller: Monitors node health
        - Replication Controller: Maintains correct number of pods
        - Endpoints Controller: Populates endpoint obejcts
        - Service Sccount Controller: Creates default accounts
-> Cloud Controller Manager(optional):
    -> Integrates with underlying cloud provider APIs
    -> Manages cloud-specific controllers:
        - Node controller(cloud-based)
        - Route controller
        - Sercice controller

// Nodes are workers machines that run containerized applications.

    Slave:

-> kubelet:
    -> Primary node agent running on each worker node
    -> Communicated with control plane via API server
    -> Ensures containers are running in Pods 
    -> Reports nodes and Pod status
    -> Executes Pod lifecycle actions
-> kube-proxy:
    -> Network proxy running on each node
    -> Maintains network rules for Pod communication
    -> Implements K8s Service abstraction
    -> Handles load balancing for services
    -> Manages iptables/IPVS rules
-> Container Runtime:
    -> Software  resposible for running containers
    -> Supprted runtime:
        - containerd(most common)
        - CRI-O
        - Docker Engine (deprecated but still used)
-> Pods:
    -> Pods are the smallest deployable units in K8s. A Pod represents a single instance of
       a running process and can contain one or more containers.
    -> Containers in Pod share network namespace (same IP)
    -> Share storage columes
    -> co-located and co-scheduled
    -> Run in a shared context
